# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]**

**Q: Differentiate between monoalphabetic and polyalphabetic substitution ciphers. Give one example of each.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | Monoalphabetic | Polyalphabetic |
|--------|----------------|----------------|
| **Definition** | A single fixed substitution mapping is used for all plaintext letters | Multiple substitution mappings are used cyclically based on a key |
| **Vulnerability** | Vulnerable to frequency analysis (letter statistics preserved) | Resists single-letter frequency analysis |
| **Example** | **Caesar Cipher** (shift by 3) | **Vigenère Cipher** (keyword-based shifting) |
| **Key Usage** | One key for entire message | Key repeats across message positions |

### Question 2 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam - June 2024]**

**Q: What is the role of the modular multiplicative inverse in Affine cipher decryption? Show how to compute $5^{-1} \mod 26$.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The modular multiplicative inverse $a^{-1}$ is required to **reverse** the encryption transformation. For Affine cipher, decryption requires:
$$
P = a^{-1}(C - b) \mod 26
$$

**Computing $5^{-1} \mod 26$:** We need $5x \equiv 1 \pmod{26}$.

Using Extended Euclidean Algorithm:
- $26 = 5 \cdot 5 + 1$
- $1 = 26 - 5 \cdot 5$
- Therefore: $5 \cdot (-5) \equiv 1 \pmod{26}$
- So: $5^{-1} \equiv -5 \equiv 21 \pmod{26}$

**Verification:** $5 \cdot 21 = 105 = 4 \cdot 26 + 1 \equiv 1 \pmod{26}$ ✓

