## KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in KTU Exams:**
> 
> 1. **Forgetting modulo operation:** Students often write $C = P + k$ without "$\mod 26$", which is **2 marks lost** in calculation questions.
> 
> 2. **Affine cipher - skipping the coprimality check:** Always verify $\gcd(a, 26) = 1$ before using $a$. Common error: using $a = 2$ or $a = 13$.
> 
> 3. **Playfair - wrong rule application:** Students confuse "same row" with "same column" rules. Remember: **same row = shift right, same column = shift down**.
> 
> 4. **Hill cipher - not checking matrix invertibility:** Always compute $\det(K) \mod 26$ and verify it's coprime with 26. Non-invertible matrices = **0 marks** for the decryption part.
> 
> 5. **Vigenère - keyword alignment error:** The keyword must align with **alphabetic characters only**, not the entire string including spaces. This is a **frequent deduction point**.
> 
> 6. **Brute force - stopping at wrong key:** Always try ALL 25 shifts. Some students stop at the first "almost readable" plaintext.
> 
> 7. **Missing negative modulo handling:** In decryption, $(C - k)$ can be negative. Always add 26 before taking modulo: $(C - k + 26) \mod 26$.

