## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Linux System Call (SYS CALL)**: A *programmatic entry point into the Linux kernel* through which a user-space process requests privileged services such as process creation, file manipulation, memory allocation, or directory traversal. In C programming, system calls are exposed via the *glibc* wrapper layer (declared in headers such as `<unistd.h>`, `<sys/stat.h>`, `<dirent.h>`).

For **PCCBL607 - Information Security Lab (KTU 2024 Scheme)**, Experiment 2 explicitly requires students to write, compile (using `gcc`) and execute C programs that demonstrate the behaviour of the following system calls:

| S.No | System Call | Header | Category |
|------|-------------|--------|----------|
| 1 | `fork()` | `<unistd.h>` | Process Control |
| 2 | `exec()` family | `<unistd.h>` | Process Control |
| 3 | `getpid()` / `getppid()` | `<unistd.h>` / `<sys/types.h>` | Process Identification |
| 4 | `exit()` | `<stdlib.h>` | Process Termination |
| 5 | `wait()` / `waitpid()` | `<sys/wait.h>` | Process Synchronization |
| 6 | `close()` | `<unistd.h>` | File Descriptor Management |
| 7 | `stat()` | `<sys/stat.h>` | File Information |
| 8 | `opendir()` | `<dirent.h>` | Directory Operations |
| 9 | `readdir()` | `<dirent.h>` | Directory Operations |

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy (The Hotel Receptionist Model)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Intuition**: Think of the **Linux Kernel** as a large, secure **Government Office** that holds all resources (files, memory, devices, processes). You (the user program) cannot walk in and grab what you want. You must approach the **reception counter (the system call interface)** and fill a formal **request form (the system call)**. The clerk checks the form, performs the action on your behalf, and hands back a **slip (the return value)** — success or an error number.

- **`fork()`** → "Make a carbon copy of my file." You and your twin both walk out of the office, each holding your own copy.
- **`exec()`** → "Throw away all the papers in my folder and refill it with the contents of File-X." Your **identity (PID) stays the same**, but the **job you do changes completely**.
- **`wait()`** → A **parent standing at the bus stop**, waiting until the child process (bus) arrives.
- **`stat()`** → "Give me the **ID card** of this file" — its size, owner, permissions, timestamps.
- **`opendir()` / `readdir()`** → "**Open the almirah drawer** and read the labels of every file in it, one by one."

### 1.3 Why this matters for Information Security

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 - CO Alignment**: This experiment maps to **CO2: "Apply process-level and file-system level security mechanisms using system programming constructs."** Understanding system calls is foundational to writing secure applications, sandboxes, shell implementations, intrusion-detection loggers, and forensic tools — all of which the KTU syllabus references in subsequent modules.

