### 3.5 Experiment 2E — File-Descriptor Lifecycle with `close()`

**Logic Steps:**
1. Open (or create) a file with `open(path, O_WRONLY $\vert$ O_CREAT $\vert$ O_TRUNC, 0644)`.
2. Print the FD returned by `open()`.
3. Write some bytes using `write(fd, "Hello\n", 6)`.
4. Call `close(fd)`.
5. Try to `write()` to the now-closed FD — observe `EBADF`.

```c
/* Program 2E — close() demo */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <errno.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(void) {
    int fd = open("demo.txt",
                  O_WRONLY $\vert$ O_CREAT $\vert$ O_TRUNC,
                  0644);
    if (fd < 0) { perror("open"); return 1; }

    printf("Opened fd = %d\n", fd);
    ssize_t n = write(fd, "Hello, Linux!\n", 14);
    printf("Wrote %zd bytes\n", n);

    if (close(fd) == -1) { perror("close"); return 1; }
    printf("Closed fd = %d\n", fd);

    /* Re-use of closed FD */
    errno = 0;
    ssize_t m = write(fd, "x", 1);
    printf("Write on closed fd: m=%zd errno=%d (%s)\n",
           m, errno, strerror(errno));
    return 0;
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Valuation Pitfall**: When a question asks to demonstrate the `close()` system call, you **must** show the consequence of using a closed FD (`EBADF`). Simply calling `close()` and `return 0` will fetch only 50% of the marks.

