### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **Q1. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Model Paper]**
> Differentiate between `fork()` and `exec()` system calls. What happens to the PID of a process when `exec()` is called?

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
`fork()` creates a **new child process** as a duplicate of the parent, returning a new PID. `exec()` **replaces the current process image** with a new program; the **PID remains unchanged**, but the text, data, heap, and stack segments of the process are overwritten with the new program. After `exec()` succeeds, the function does not return. *(Examiner gives full 3 marks only if the "PID remains same" fact is explicitly stated.)*

---

> **Q2. [KTU University Exam — June 2024, Sample Question Paper]**
> Why must a parent process call `wait()` after `fork()`? What is a "zombie process"?

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
A terminated child retains an entry in the kernel's process table until the parent reaps its exit status. Such an entry is called a **zombie** (`Z` state in `ps`). `wait()` (or `waitpid()`) reads the status and allows the kernel to free the table entry. Failure to call `wait()` causes a **resource leak** and, when the table is full, prevents new processes from being created.

---

### 5.2 Part B — 14-Mark Long Answer (Internal Choice)

> **Question A — [KTU 2024 Model, Module 2]**
> **(a) [7 marks]** Write a C program that uses `fork()` to create a child process. The child process should execute the command `ls -l /tmp` using `execlp()`. The parent process should wait for the child to finish and print its exit status using `waitpid()` and the `WEXITSTATUS` macro. Include proper error checking.
>
> **(b) [7 marks]** Explain the role of the following system calls in your program: `fork`, `execlp`, `waitpid`, `exit`, and `getpid`. Also draw a neat flowchart of the execution flow.

**Model Solution (a) — 7 marks:**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main(void) {
    pid_t pid = fork();
    if (pid < 0) { perror("fork"); return EXIT_FAILURE; }

    if (pid == 0) {                       /* CHILD */
        printf("[CHILD %d] running ls -l /tmp\n", getpid());
        execlp("ls", "ls", "-l", "/tmp", (char *)NULL);
        perror("execlp");
        exit(127);                         /* exec failure */
    }

    /* PARENT */
    int status;
    waitpid(pid, &status, 0);
    if (WIFEXITED(status))
        printf("[PARENT] child exited with code %d\n",
               WEXITSTATUS(status));
    else if (WIFSIGNALED(status))
        printf("[PARENT] child killed by signal %d\n",
               WTERMSIG(status));
    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

**Mark split:**
- 1 mark: Correct `fork()` return-value handling
- 2 marks: Correct `execlp` invocation with NULL terminator
- 2 marks: Correct `waitpid` + macro usage
- 1 mark: Proper headers and `perror` error handling
- 1 mark: Output observations

**Model Solution (b) — 7 marks:**

| Call | Role (1 mark each, last 2 for flowchart) |
|------|-------------------------------------------|
| `fork` | Duplicates the process so child can run a new program. Returns 0 to child and child-PID to parent. |
| `execlp` | Replaces the child's image with `ls`. Searches `PATH` for the binary. Variadic; terminated by `NULL`. |
| `waitpid` | Suspends parent until the **specific** child terminates; writes status into `&status`. |
| `exit` | Called by the child **only if `execlp` fails** (status 127). In a successful run, the child simply returns from `main` and the C runtime calls `exit`. |
| `getpid` | Used for diagnostic printing of the child PID in the output. |

**Flowchart:** (Use the diagram in Section 4.1 — print and attach.)

