# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Programs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Program 1 — Basic `open` + `read` + `write` (File Copy Utility)

This program copies the contents of `source.txt` into `dest.txt` using raw system calls — the **canonical KTU lab exercise**.

```c
/*
 * Program: sys_copy.c
 * Lab:     PCCBL607 - Information Security Lab
 * Topic:   Module Experiment 2 - Linux I/O System Calls
 * Build:   gcc sys_copy.c -o sys_copy
 * Run:     ./sys_copy source.txt dest.txt
 */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <fcntl.h>      // For open(), O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY, O_CREAT, O_TRUNC
#include <unistd.h>     // For read(), write(), close()
#include <errno.h>      // For errno and strerror()
#include <string.h>     // For strerror()

#define BUF_SIZE 1024

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    int  src_fd, dst_fd, n_read, n_written;
    char buffer[BUF_SIZE];
    char *buf_ptr;
    int  remaining;

    /* ---- STEP 1: Argument validation ---- */
    if (argc != 3) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Usage: %s <source> <destination>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    /* ---- STEP 2: open() the source file read-only ---- */
    src_fd = open(argv[1], O_RDONLY);
    if (src_fd < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Error opening source '%s': %s\n",
                argv[1], strerror(errno));
        return 1;
    }
    printf("[OK] Opened source '%s' with fd = %d\n", argv[1], src_fd);

    /* ---- STEP 3: open() the destination file write/create/truncate ---- */
    dst_fd = open(argv[2], O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, 0644);
    if (dst_fd < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Error opening destination '%s': %s\n",
                argv[2], strerror(errno));
        close(src_fd);
        return 1;
    }
    printf("[OK] Opened destination '%s' with fd = %d\n", argv[2], dst_fd);

    /* ---- STEP 4: read() / write() loop ---- */
    while ((n_read = read(src_fd, buffer, BUF_SIZE)) > 0) {
        buf_ptr    = buffer;
        remaining  = n_read;

        /* Handle short writes (loop until all bytes are written) */
        while (remaining > 0) {
            n_written = write(dst_fd, buf_ptr, remaining);
            if (n_written < 0) {
                if (errno == EINTR) continue;   // Interrupted, retry
                fprintf(stderr, "write() failed: %s\n", strerror(errno));
                close(src_fd);
                close(dst_fd);
                return 1;
            }
            remaining -= n_written;
            buf_ptr   += n_written;
        }
    }

    if (n_read < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "read() failed: %s\n", strerror(errno));
    }

    /* ---- STEP 5: close() both file descriptors ---- */
    close(src_fd);
    close(dst_fd);
    printf("[OK] File copy complete.\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.1.1 Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthrough

| Step | System Call | Man Page Section | Purpose in This Program |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | — | — | Validate `argc` to ensure user passed source + destination |
| 2 | `open(argv[1], O_RDONLY)` | `man 2 open` | Open existing file for reading; returns fd 3 (usually) |
| 3 | `open(argv[2], O_WRONLY \vert O_CREAT \vert O_TRUNC, 0644)` | `man 2 open` | Create file if missing, empty it if it exists, perms = rw-r--r-- |
| 4 | `read(src_fd, buffer, 1024)` | `man 2 read` | Pull up to 1024 bytes from kernel into `buffer` |
| 5 | `write(dst_fd, buf_ptr, remaining)` | `man 2 write` | Push bytes from `buf_ptr` to destination file |
| 6 | `close(src_fd)` / `close(dst_fd)` | `man 2 close` | Release kernel resources and free fd slots |

### 3.1.2 Why the Short-Write Loop is Required

The POSIX standard guarantees that `read()` will return **at most** `count` bytes, but it may return fewer (e.g., near EOF, on a pipe, on a network socket, or after a signal). Similarly, `write()` is allowed to return a value *less than* `count` (a "short write"). For a correct, robust file-copy implementation — which is mandatory for any security-sensitive program — the outer loop handles short reads and the inner loop handles short writes.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Viva Favorite Question:** *"What happens if `read()` returns fewer bytes than requested?"* 
> **Model Answer:** "The kernel may return fewer bytes than requested due to EOF, signals, or pipe/socket semantics. A robust program must check the return value and loop until exactly the expected number of bytes (or EOF) is reached."

## 3.2 Program 2 — Demonstrating `O_APPEND` (Atomic Append Semantics)

```c
/*
 * Program: append_demo.c
 * Purpose: Show that O_APPEND makes write() atomic at the end-of-file
 */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <errno.h>

int main(void) {
    const char *msg = "Log entry from PID\n";
    int fd;

    /* O_APPEND ensures every write() goes to end-of-file atomically,
       even if multiple processes open the same file concurrently.   */
    fd = open("shared.log", O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_APPEND, 0644);
    if (fd < 0) {
        perror("open");
        return 1;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        if (write(fd, msg, strlen(msg)) < 0) {
            perror("write");
            close(fd);
            return 1;
        }
    }

    close(fd);
    printf("[OK] Appended 5 entries to shared.log\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.2.1 Analytical Reasoning

When two processes open the same log file simultaneously without `O_APPEND`, a race condition can occur: process A seeks to position 100, process B seeks to position 100, both write — overwriting each other. The POSIX standard specifies that when `O_APPEND` is set, the kernel performs an **atomic lseek-to-EOF + write** under the inode's lock. This is the foundation of safe logging in multi-process servers.

$$ \text{Atomic Action with } O\_APPEND: \quad \text{seek}(f\_pos = \text{file\_size}) \;\Vert\; \text{write}(\text{user\_buf}) $$

## 3.3 Program 3 — Inspecting File Descriptors via `/proc/self/fd`

```c
/*
 * Program: fd_inspect.c
 * Purpose: Print the /proc/self/fd entries to show kernel-managed fds
 */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <dirent.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(void) {
    int fd = open("example.txt", O_CREAT | O_WRONLY, 0644);
    if (fd < 0) { perror("open"); return 1; }

    printf("File descriptor returned: %d\n", fd);
    printf("Listing /proc/self/fd:\n");
    system("ls -l /proc/self/fd");

    write(fd, "Hello from raw syscall!\n", 24);
    close(fd);

    return 0;
}
```

### 3.3.1 Analytical Observation

When you run this program, you'll observe that **fd 0, 1, 2** always point to the terminal (stdin/stdout/stderr), and the new file gets **fd 3** (or the next available integer). This empirically proves the file descriptor allocation rule:

$$ fd_{new} = \min \{ i \in \mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0} \mid \text{slot } i \text{ is free in the process fd table} \} $$

## 3.4 Derivation — Total Bytes Copied After N Loop Iterations

For Program 1, suppose the source file is **S** bytes long and the buffer size is **B** bytes. After **N** complete read iterations, the total bytes written to the destination is:

$$ N = \left\lceil \frac{S}{B} \right\rceil = \left\lfloor \frac{S + B - 1}{B} \right\rfloor $$

The exact byte count transferred is:

$$ T = \sum_{i=1}^{N} r_i \quad \text{where} \quad r_i = \min(B,\; S - B \cdot (i-1)) $$

For a cleanly-aligned file where $S = kB$ for some integer $k$:

$$ T = k \cdot B = S \quad \text{(no residual partial read)} $$

For a non-aligned file where $S = kB + r$ with $0 < r < B$:

$$ T = kB + r = S \quad \text{(final iteration reads exactly } r \text{ bytes, then returns 0 on next call)} $$

> [!NOTE]
> This last equation confirms why `read()` returning 0 (EOF) terminates the while-loop correctly — the kernel reports EOF only when the file position equals file size, so a short final read is still followed by a zero-byte read that signals termination.

## 3.5 Error Handling Matrix (Mandatory for KTU Lab Viva)

| `errno` Value | Numeric Code | Common Cause | Correct Program Response |
|---|---|---|---|
| `EACCES` | 13 | Permission denied | Print error, exit non-zero |
| `EEXIST` | 17 | `O_CREAT \vert O_EXCL` and file exists | Print error, exit non-zero |
| `ENOENT` | 2 | File not found | Print error, exit non-zero |
| `EBADF` | 9 | Invalid fd passed to `read`/`write` | Print error, exit non-zero |
| `EINTR` | 4 | System call interrupted by signal | Retry the call |
| `EAGAIN` | 11 | Non-blocking I/O would block | Retry later (or yield) |
| `ENOSPC` | 28 | No space left on device | Print error, exit non-zero |
| `EIO` | 5 | Low-level I/O error | Print error, exit non-zero |

