# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **Question 1 [KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model Paper]**
> **Define the `open()` system call in Linux. List any four flags that can be passed to it and explain the purpose of `O_CREAT | O_EXCL` combination.**

**Model Answer:**

The `open()` system call (declared in `<fcntl.h>`) is the primary kernel interface used to obtain a file descriptor for a specified file path. It requests the kernel to resolve the pathname, check permissions, optionally create the file, and allocate a new file descriptor in the calling process's fd table.

Four important flags:

1. **`O_RDONLY`** (value 0) — Open the file for reading only.
2. **`O_WRONLY`** (value 1) — Open the file for writing only.
3. **`O_RDWR`** (value 2) — Open the file for both reading and writing.
4. **`O_APPEND`** (value 1024 / 0x400) — All writes automatically go to end-of-file.

**Purpose of `O_CREAT | O_EXCL`:** When combined, this pair creates the file *only if it does not already exist*. If the file already exists, `open()` fails and returns `-1` with `errno = EEXIST`. This combination is the standard POSIX way to **atomically create a file**, preventing race conditions in multi-process scenarios — a fundamental security primitive in file-locking and lock-file creation.

---

> **Question 2 [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
> **Differentiate between `read()` and `fread()`. Why is the raw `read()` system call preferred in information security applications?**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | `read()` System Call | `fread()` Library Function |
|---|---|---|
| Header | `<unistd.h>` | `<stdio.h>` |
| Layer | Kernel-level (direct syscall) | User-space library (buffered) |
| Buffering | Unbuffered (immediate) | Buffered (BUFSIZ = 8192 bytes) |
| Return type | `ssize_t` (signed, indicates errors) | `size_t` (unsigned) |
| File handle | File descriptor (int) | `FILE *` stream |
| Atomicity per call | Reads up to N bytes, may return less | Reads N * size objects |
| Error reporting | Sets `errno` | Sets `errno` and stream error flag |

**Why preferred in security apps:**
- **Byte-level precision** required for cryptographic operations.
- **No unintended buffering** that could leak data through core dumps or memory.
- **Direct control** over partial reads, EOF detection, and atomic append semantics.
- **Compatibility with low-level features** like `O_NOFOLLOW`, `O_SYNC`, and `mmap()`.

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, with Internal Choice)

> **Question A (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**

**Write a C program using Linux system calls `open()`, `read()`, `write()`, and `close()` to implement a file-copy utility that copies the contents of one file to another. Explain each system call, its prototype, return values, and how the program handles short reads and short writes. Also explain the significance of file descriptors in Linux.**

### (a) C Program with Full Explanation — 7 Marks

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <errno.h>
#include <string.h>

#define BUF_SIZE 1024

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    int  src_fd, dst_fd, n_read, n_written;
    char buffer[BUF_SIZE];
    char *buf_ptr;
    int  remaining;

    if (argc != 3) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Usage: %s <source> <dest>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    src_fd = open(argv[1], O_RDONLY);
    if (src_fd < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "open source: %s\n", strerror(errno));
        return 1;
    }

    dst_fd = open(argv[2], O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, 0644);
    if (dst_fd < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "open dest: %s\n", strerror(errno));
        close(src_fd);
        return 1;
    }

    while ((n_read = read(src_fd, buffer, BUF_SIZE)) > 0) {
        buf_ptr   = buffer;
        remaining = n_read;
        while (remaining > 0) {
            n_written = write(dst_fd, buf_ptr, remaining);
            if (n_written < 0) {
                if (errno == EINTR) continue;
                perror("write");
                close(src_fd); close(dst_fd);
                return 1;
            }
            remaining -= n_written;
            buf_ptr   += n_written;
        }
    }

    if (n_read < 0) perror("read");
    close(src_fd);
    close(dst_fd);
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of each syscall:**

- **`open(pathname, flags, mode)`** — Returns a new fd; on failure returns -1. Used twice: once read-only for source, once write/create/truncate for destination. The `0644` mode sets `-rw-r--r--` permissions on the new file.
- **`read(fd, buf, count)`** — Reads up to `count` bytes from `fd` into `buf`. Returns number of bytes read, 0 for EOF, or -1 on error. We use a `while` loop because the kernel is allowed to return fewer bytes than requested.
- **`write(fd, buf, count)`** — Writes up to `count` bytes from `buf` to `fd`. We loop with a `buf_ptr` to handle short writes (also legal per POSIX).
- **`close(fd)`** — Releases the fd slot in the process's fd table. Always check the return value in production code.

### (b) File Descriptor Concept and Significance — 7 Marks

A **file descriptor (fd)** is a small non-negative integer that the kernel uses as an index into the per-process file descriptor table. Each process inherits three standard fds: **0 (stdin)**, **1 (stdout)**, **2 (stderr)**. The first user-opened file typically gets fd 3.

The fd is the user-space handle to kernel-managed resources. When `open()` succeeds, the kernel creates an entry in the system-wide open-file table (a `struct file` in Linux source) containing the file offset, access mode, and pointers to the underlying inode operations. The fd is just an *index* into the per-process array that points to this `struct file`.

**Significance:**
- **Unified I/O abstraction** — pipes, sockets, terminals, regular files, and devices all use the same fd-based interface.
- **Process isolation** — Each process has its own fd table; fds are not shared by default.
- **Inheritance** — fds are inherited across `fork()` and preserved across `exec()`, enabling redirection and pipelines.
- **Security enforcement** — Permission checks happen at `open()` time, and the fd then becomes the credential for all subsequent operations.

