## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Where KTU Students Commonly Lose Marks on This Topic:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting to check the return value of `open()`, `read()`, and `write()`.** A program that compiles and "seems to work" without error checking will lose at least **2-3 marks** in the lab record and the ESE viva.
> 2. **Using `fopen()`/`fread()`/`fwrite()` instead of `open()`/`read()`/`write()`.** The lab *explicitly* requires system calls. Mixing the two will attract partial deductions.
> 3. **Confusing `O_RDONLY = 0` with the file being "non-existent."** Students often write `open(path, 1)` thinking `1` is the fd number — it is actually the *flag value* `O_WRONLY`.
> 4. **Missing `O_TRUNC` when "creating" a destination file.** Without `O_TRUNC`, the new file may contain leftover bytes from a previous run that are longer than the new content.
> 5. **Wrong mode argument.** `open(path, O_CREAT, 0644)` requires the *third* argument (mode). Forgetting it gives files with random permissions (often `000` or `600`), which then causes `EACCES` on subsequent access.
> 6. **Not handling `EINTR`.** In a robust program, system calls interrupted by signals should be retried. Markers may deduct 1 mark for this in the ESE.
> 7. **Confusing `BUFSIZ` (stdio) with arbitrary buffer size.** The KTU lab expects you to *declare your own* buffer (e.g., `char buf[1024];`) for the `read`/`write` calls.

