## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!TIP]
> **High-Density Revision Checklist for PCCBL607 Module 2:**

- ✅ `open()` returns a **file descriptor (fd)**, a non-negative integer. Failure returns **-1** with `errno` set.
- ✅ Standard fds: **0 = stdin**, **1 = stdout**, **2 = stderr**. The first user fd is typically **3**.
- ✅ `read(fd, buf, n)` returns the number of bytes read, **0 at EOF**, or **-1** on error.
- ✅ `write(fd, buf, n)` may perform a **short write** — always check the return value.
- ✅ `close(fd)` releases the fd slot; always close fds to prevent resource leaks.
- ✅ `O_CREAT` requires a third argument: the file **mode** (e.g., `0644` = rw-r--r--).
- ✅ `O_EXCL` combined with `O_CREAT` = **atomic file creation** (fails if file exists).
- ✅ `O_TRUNC` empties the file if it already exists.
- ✅ `O_APPEND` makes every `write()` go to end-of-file **atomically** (race-free logging).
- ✅ Use `<fcntl.h>` for `open()` and flags; use `<unistd.h>` for `read`/`write`/`close`.
- ✅ Use `<errno.h>` + `<string.h>` + `strerror(errno)` for **error reporting**.
- ✅ Short reads and short writes **must** be handled with proper loops in robust code.
- ✅ Compile with `gcc filename.c -o filename` and run with `./filename args`.
- ✅ Verify fds at runtime via `ls -l /proc/self/fd` (empirical proof of fd allocation).
- ✅ For security-sensitive programs, prefer raw syscalls over buffered `stdio` functions.
- ✅ The `O_NOFOLLOW` flag (0x20000) prevents symlink traversal during `open()` — a key security primitive.
- ✅ Remember the octal values: `O_CREAT=0100`, `O_EXCL=0200`, `O_TRUNC=01000`, `O_APPEND=02000`.

